The Advia Centaur PSA assay is a two site sandwich immunoassay using direct chemiluminometric technology. Values obtained with different assay methods are not interchangeable. Do not interpret levels of PSA as absolute evidence of the presence or the absence of malignant disease.
Measurement of serum PSA levels alone is not recommended as a screening procedure for the diagnosis of cancer.
Do not predict disease recurrence solely on serial PSA values.

Natriuretic peptide B [Mass/volume] in Serum or Plasma (test code = 30934-4)

COMMENT: Elevated BNP levels correlate with CHF. Interpretation depends on age, sex, other tests, etc. A cutoff of 100 pg/ml is a recommended balance of specificity and sensitivity. Higher cutoff levels have higher specificity and lower sensitivity. Results above 100 pg/ml do not necessarily indicate CHF. Approximately 20% of people with CHF have BNP less than 100 pg/ml. Levels above 250 pg/ml are rare without CHF. Results below 100 pg/ml do not necessarily indicate absence of CHF. Contact the Chemistry department for more information at 583-8747.

Fibrin D-dimer FEU [Mass/volume] in Platelet poor plasma (test code = 48065-7)

*** Suggestive Cut off: 400 ng/mL D-DU *** "D-DU = D-DIMER UNITS"
Please Note: Results of D-Dimer assays should always be interpreted in conjunction with the patient's medical history, clinical presentation and other findings.
The Biosite Triage Meter performs this assay by the flourescence immunoassay method. Subsequent assays may not use this method and may not have the same reference range. All clinical decisions should be made based on the specified assay range and other clinical information.
